title: Improve react typings for HTML attributes, fix related tests/typings in other libraries
body:
React's HTML attributes definition is currently done in a single object : `HTMLAttributes` this makes it really difficult to create custom components that extend HTML elements because attributes of other elements (not even applicable in many components) come in the way of defining your own new attributes/props. Example : you want to create a Component that creates a `, T extends HTMLElement>` that is more precise than `ReactHTMLElement` - Added `DetailedHTMLFactory

, T extends HTMLElement>` that is more precise than ` HTMLFactory` - Added `DetailedHTMLProps, T>` that is more precise than `HTMLProps` - Added `AllHTMLAttributes` that has the same behaviour as the old `HTMLAttributes` - Added an interface for each HTML element that has custom attributes - Changed `React.DOM.*` and `JSX.IntrinsicElements.*` to use these new interfaces - Removed `ChangeTargetHTMLFactory`, `ChangeTargetHTMLProps` and `ChangeTargetHTMLAttributes`, replaced by `DetailedHTMLFactory`, `DetailedHTMLProps` and custom interfaces for input, textarea and select elements - Fixed tests for `material-ui`, `react-dropzone`, `react-input-mask`, `react-router-dom`, `react-router`, `react-user-tour` and `reactstrap` I did the changes in this way (introducing new `Detailed*` interfaces in order to keep existing code working in applications that directly rely on the existing interfaces in their applications. Two things I'm not entirely sure about are: - Why are the dom typings in `react` and not `react-dom` ? - Should I move the even attributes to their respective attributes classes if they're not applicable elsewhere or leave them in `DOMAttributes` ?

The current typings do not allow this callback to be specified.

title: [stripe-node] cvc must be a string, as it may have leading zeros
body:
I believe the type currently assigned to the `cvc` field on `ISourceCreationOptions` is incorrect. At the moment, it is a `number` which means that if your cvc number is `012`, stripe will fail the payment because there will not be a leading zero on `12`. Instead, it must be sent as a string so that the leading zeros are retained. I have verified the error occurs as described here, and that changing the type fixes the error and allows stripe to process the charge.

The Stripe API docs online are unusually vague when discussing the `cvc` (https://stripe.com/docs/api/node#create_charge). They do not say what the type is, nor do they have any example code that demonstrates a charge with a card source. The full text at the moment is:

> Card security code. Highly recommended to always include this value, but it's only required for accounts based in European countries.

The best proof that this is a valid change is, I think, to look at stripe's own librarys for other languages which are typed. For example, here are links to the `cvc` definition in the `go` and `dotnet` libs:

https://github.com/stripe/stripe-go/blob/master/card.go#L33
https://github.com/stripe/stripe-dotnet/blob/master/src/Stripe.net/Services/_sources/SourceCard.cs#L22
